==Ancient Greek==

===Pronunciation===
*εὐαγγέλιον / euaggelion / yoo-ang-ghel'-ee-on
*From the same as [[εὐαγγελίζω]] {{GG|2097}}; a good message, that is, the gospel:

===Noun===
'''εὐαγγέλιον'''

# [[gospel]].

===Etymology===
Initially, the word meant "good messenger", the prefix "eu" meaning "good" and "angelion" meaning "messenger" (from the same word that means "angel") and was used to describe the runners who brought news in ancient Greece. It only came to mean "good message" or "good news" over time and eventually became most commonly associated with the Christian gospels.

===Transliterations===
*euaggelion
*euangelion
*evangelion

